nodes.info: The agribusiness sector includes a diverse group of interests -- crop producers, livestock and meat producers, poultry and egg companies, dairy farmers, timber producers, tobacco companies and food manufacturers and stores. The communications and electronics sector includes a wide variety of industries: printing and publishing, entertainment, telecommunications, electronics manufacturing and Internet companies. This sector includes general contractors, home builders, special trade contractors (such as electricians and plumbers), construction services and building material and equipment companies. TAMKO Building Products  $3,954,136 Coastal Construction Group   $3,046,595 Rooney Holdings  $2,926,687 National Assn of Home Builders   $2,112,041 American Council of Engineering Cos  $1,877,000

Although the defense sector contributes far less money to politicians than many other sectors, it is one of the most powerful in politics.The sector includes defense aerospace, defense electronics and other miscellaneous defense companies. Lockheed Martin  $3,996,296 Northrop Grumman   $3,036,473 Boeing Co  $2,972,768 Raytheon Co  $2,147,804 General Dynamics   $1,551,761

Led by the oil and gas industry, this sector regularly pumps the vast majority of its campaign contributions into Republican coffers. Even as other traditionally GOP-inclined industries have shifted somewhat to the left, this sector has remained rock-solid red.   Koch Industries  $9,192,265 Chevron Corp   $4,555,703 Ariel Corp   $4,405,115 Stewart & Stevenson  $4,028,156 Alliance Coal  $3,313,710 Western Refining   $3,067,402

The financial sector is far and away the largest source of campaign contributions to federal candidates and parties, with insurance companies, securities and investment firms, real estate interests and commercial banks providing the bulk of that money.   Renaissance Technologies   $51,065,972 Paloma Partners  $38,514,900 Elliott Management   $24,428,195 Soros Fund Management  $22,752,815 Bloomberg Lp   $22,069,026 Pritzker Group   $21,039,522

Physicians and other health professionals are traditionally the largest source of federal campaign contributions in this sector, which contributed a record $260.4 million to federal candidates during the 2012 election cycle. Aside from doctors' associations, pharmaceutical companies and HMOs are consistently generous givers. Certain industries within the sector, such as nurses, give more generously to Democrats, but on the whole Republicans traditionally have gained the most from contributions by health interests.   Adelson Drug Clinic  $15,258,800 Slim-Fast Foods  $7,322,300 DE Shaw Research   $4,770,588 Exoxemis Inc   $3,524,700 Besilu Stables (Benjamin Leon Jr)  $3,500,000 Platinum Health Care   $2,444,600

The most notable interests in this grouping - including the powerful American Association for Justice - belong to the plaintiffs' bar. The sector also includes lobbyists at firms representing countless clients on Capitol Hill and before the Obama administration.   American Assn for Justice  $2,902,010 Mostyn Law Firm  $2,526,891 Jones Day  $2,404,929 Akin, Gump et al   $2,260,035 Sullivan & Cromwell  $1,851,430 Kirkland & Ellis   $1,824,751

Four industries - air, automotive, rail and sea transport -- make up the bulk of the transportation sector; the size of their political contributions comes in that order. Yet many of the sector's top donors are delivery service organizations -- UPS and FedEx are among the top four contributors -- and car dealerships also count for a significant portion of the funds. The industry has leaned Republican in every election cycle beginning in 1990 through 2012. Braman Motorcars   $7,400,598 National Auto Dealers Assn   $3,434,488 United Parcel Service  $3,195,524 BNSF Railway   $2,527,004 Union Pacific Corp   $1,970,897

The broad miscellaneous business grouping includes manufacturing, textiles, steel, chemicals, consumer retail goods, restaurants, beer wholesalers and funeral services. Also part of this sector are the gambling, tourism, and food and beverage industries. Las Vegas Sands  $31,428,771 Uline Inc  $20,102,382 Jobs Ohio  $10,001,000 World Wrestling Entertainment  $9,677,228 Houston Texans   $7,692,790

The labor sector has experienced decreasing political power in recent years. The past generation has been marked by a changing economy, a pattern of deregulation, and decreasing union membership. In 2012, only 11.3 percent of workers belonged to unions compared to 20.1 percent in 1983. National Education Assn  $23,356,418 Carpenters & Joiners Union   $14,261,217 AFL-CIO  $11,288,274 American Fedn of St/Cnty/Munic Employees   $9,699,666 For Our Future   $7,464,313

This sector is made up of a diverse crowd of organizations that are primarily partisan or focus on a single-issue area such as abortion, the environment, gun rights or foreign policy. Many of these groups -- the National Rifle Association, EMILY's List -- are well known and capable of launching high-profile media campaigns to mobilize their members. Republican Governors Assn  $15,575,750 Priorities USA/Priorities USA Action   $15,133,955 Nextgen Climate Action   $11,426,936 One Nation   $11,000,000 Environment America  $8,293,796 Senate Leadership Fund   $7,635,200

This sector is home to a variety of industries that don't fall under any business, labor or ideological groupings. The biggest dollars, by far, come from the large and diverse group of donors listing their occupation as retired.
